      <p>Follow the supplement facts panel. Most require 2 gummies per serving. Taking only 1 delivers half the labeled nutrients. Do not exceed the recommended serving — fat-soluble vitamins accumulate. Review total intake if taking multiple supplements.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Which gummy supplements have the most scientific evidence?</summary>
      <p>Ranked: (1) Creatine — 500+ studies. (2) Vitamin D3 — extensive deficiency and health evidence. (3) Omega-3 — cardiovascular and cognitive meta-analyses. (4) Melatonin — well-established for sleep. (5) Magnesium — sleep, stress, muscle evidence. (6) Ashwagandha — 12+ RCTs. (7) Elderberry — respiratory infection meta-analysis. (8) Collagen — 11 skin RCTs.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between cheap and expensive gummy vitamins?</summary>
      <p>Price differences reflect ingredient quality (bioavailable forms), third-party testing (USP costs more), and brand positioning. A $10 USP Verified gummy may exceed a $30 unverified premium brand in quality. Check the supplement facts panel and certifications, not just the price.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can adults take too many gummy vitamins?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K) accumulate and can cause toxicity. Iron is a poisoning risk in large quantities. Even B6 can cause nerve damage at extreme doses. Follow labeled serving sizes, store out of reach of children, and calculate total intake across all supplements.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What gummy vitamins do doctors recommend?</summary>
      <p>Nature Made (USP Verified, #1 pharmacist-recommended), Centrum (most trusted multivitamin), and Nordic Naturals (omega-3 purity). Ask your physician to test vitamin D levels and order a metabolic panel to identify your specific supplementation needs.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When is the best time to take gummy vitamins?</summary>
      <p>With a fat-containing meal for fat-soluble vitamin absorption. Melatonin: 30-60 min before bed. Magnesium for sleep: 30-60 min before bed. B-vitamins: morning (mild energy effect). Creatine: any time, just be consistent. Iron: empty stomach or with vitamin C, away from calcium and coffee.</p>
    </details>

